      "titleArabic": "الْجُمْلَة الاسْمِيَّة",
      "content": [
        "A nominal sentence (جملة اسمية) begins with a noun. It consists of two parts: the subject (مبتدأ/mubtada') and the predicate (خبر/khabar). Both are in the nominative case.",
        "The predicate can be an adjective, prepositional phrase, adverb, or another noun. There is no verb 'to be' in the present tense - the meaning 'is/are' is implied."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Nominal sentences start with a noun: الطَّالِبُ مُجْتَهِدٌ",
        "Subject (مبتدأ) + Predicate (خبر)",
        "Both parts are nominative (مرفوع) with damma",
        "No 'is/are' verb needed in present tense Arabic"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "الْكِتَابُ جَدِيدٌ", "english": "The book is new" },
